{
  "lesson_number": 30,
  "title": "Lesson 30",
  "topic": "Adjectives ending in -vantu/-mantu",
  "grammar": {
    "explanations": [
      "Attributive adjectives ending in -vantu and -mantu can be declined in all three genders. They agree with the nouns they qualify in gender, number and case.",
      "In the masculine gender, the adjective guṇavantu (virtuous) is declined as follows. Note the similarities of this declension to the declension of the present participle masculine gender ending in -nta. Adjectives ending in -mantu are declined as cakkhumā, cakkhumanto etc.",
      "In the neuter gender, only the nominative and accusative forms differ from the masculine: singular ojavantaṃ and plural ojavantāni. The rest is similar to the declension of masculine adjectives ending in -vantu and -mantu.",
      "The feminine forms of adjectives ending in -vantu are guṇavatī / guṇavantī, and for -mantu they are cakkhumatī / cakkhumantī. These feminine forms are declined like kumārī, i.e. feminine nouns ending in -ī."
    ],
